                <note rend="inline" type="source">550 E 1/62: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Child</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-03-01T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 1, 1922—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 2—3:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>30. Italian Government has received from Russia a telegraphic reply to Italy’s
                    announcement of postponement of the Genoa Conference. The reply, signed by
                    Chicherin, accepts postponement but contains extraordinary insolence and abuse
                    of purposes and policies of so-called capitalistic nations, especially Italy.
                    Text has not been published but personnel of Foreign Office considers Russian
                    reply an attempt to make a large gesture of political importance to hide
                    economic desperation. Something may be forecast of Russia’s attitude at the
                    conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Child</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
